nknown \n|flag={{flag|Nazi Germany}}\n|desc=World War II: The harbor tug was sunk by a mine in the harbor of Odessa.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.soviet-empire.com/ussr/viewtopic.php?f=149&t=53917 |title=FR 1 class river minesweepers,Germany |publisher=SovietEmpire |accessdate=23 December 2019}}</ref>  \n}}\n{{shipwreck list end}}\n\n==23 April==\n{{shipwreck list begin |date=23 April 1942 |sort=}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Asuncion||2}} \n|flag={{flagcountry|Nazi Germany}}\n|desc=[[World War II]]: The [[transport ship]] struck a [[naval mine|mine]] and sank in [[Kv\u00e6nangen (fjord)|Kv\u00e6nangen]].<ref name=seekrieg194204/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Chatwood||2}} \n|flag={{flag|United Kingdom|civil}}\n|desc=World War II: The cargo ship struck a mine and sank in the [[North Sea]] off [[Cromer]], [[Norfolk]].<ref name=seekrieg194204/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Connecticut||2}} \n|flag={{flag|United States|1912}}\n|desc=World War II: The tanker was [[torpedo]]ed and sunk in the Atlantic Ocean ({{Coord|23|00|S|15|00|W}}) by {{ship|German motor torpedo boat|LS-4||2}} ({{navy|Nazi Germany}}) operating from {{ship|German auxiliary cruiser|Michel||2}} ({{navy|Nazi Germany}}) with the loss of 24 of her crew and 11 Naval Armed Guards. 18 survivors were rescued by {{ship|German auxiliary cruiser|Michel||2}} ({{navy|Nazi Germany}}) and eventually turned over to the Japanese as P.O.W.s.<ref>{{cite web | title=Connecticut Tanker 1938-1942 | url=http://www.wrecksite.eu/wreck.aspx?136783 |publisher=Wrecksite.eu | accessdate=23 April 2013 }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{MV|Jersey|1936|2}} \n|flag={{flag|United Kingdom|civil}}\n|desc=World War II: The cargo ship struck a mine and sank in the [[Red Sea]] off [[Suez]], Egypt.<ref name=seekrieg194204/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Kirkland||2}} \n|flag={{flag|United Kingdom|civil}}\n|desc=World War II: [[Convoy TA 36]]: The cargo ship was torpedoed and sunk in the [[Mediterranean Sea]] {{convert|35|nmi|km}} north west of [[Sidi Barrani]], Egypt ({{Coord|31|51|N|26|37|E}}) by {{GS|U-565||2}} ({{navy|Nazi Germany}}) with the loss of one of her 23 crew. Survivors were rescued by {{HMT|Falk|FY789|6}} ({{navy|UK}}).<ref name=Kirkland>{{cite web |url= http://uboat.net/allies/merchants/ships/1563.html |title=Kirkland |publisher=Uboat |accessdate=9 April 2012}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Lammot Du Pont||2}} \n|flag={{flag|United States|1912}}\n|desc=World War II: The cargo ship was torpedoed and sunk in the Atlantic Ocean {{convert|500|nmi|km}} south east of Bermuda ({{coord|27|10|N|57|10|W}}) by {{GS|U-125|1940|2}} ({{navy|Nazi Germany}}) with the loss of 17 of her 54 crew. Survivors were rescued by {{MV|Astri||2}} ({{flag|Sweden}}) and {{USS|Tarbell|DD-142|6}} ({{navy|USA|1912}}).<ref\nname=LDP>{{cite web |url= http://uboat.net/allies/merchants/ships/1565.html |title=Lammot Du Pont |publisher=Uboat |accessdate=22 February 2012}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Stensaas||2}} \n|flag={{flag|Norway}}\n|desc=World War II: The cargo ship was torpedoed and sunk in the [[Barents Sea]] off [[Slettnes Lighthouse|Slettnes]], Norway ({{coord|71|04|N|28|20|E}}) by {{ship|Soviet submarine|SC-401||2}} ({{navy|Soviet Union}}). The crew were rescued by {{ship|German submarine chaser|UJ-1101||2}} ({{navy|Nazi Germany}}).<ref name=HomeSo>{{cite web |url=http://www.warsailors.com/homefleet/shipss2.html |title=Norwegian Homefleet - WW II, Ships starting with So through S\u00f8 |publisher=Warsailors |accessdate=11 February 2012}}</ref> }}\n{{shipwreck list end}}\n\n==24 April==\n{{shipwreck list begin |date=24 April 1942 |sort=}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{MV|Empire Drum||2}} \n|flag={{Flag|United Kingdom|civil}}\n|desc=World War II: The cargo ship was torpedoed and sunk in the [[Atlantic Ocean]], {{convert|280|nmi|km}} south east of [[New York City|New York]], United States ({{coord|37|00|N|69|15|W}}) by {{GS|U-136|1941|2}} ({{navy|Nazi Germany}}). All 41 crew survived, they were rescued by {{USS|Roper|DD-147|6}} ({{navy|USA|1912}}) and {{MV|Venezia||2}} ({{flag|Sweden}}).\n}}\n{{shipwreck list end}}\n\n==25 April==\n{{shipwreck list begin |date=25 April 1942 |sort=}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Leesee||2}} \n|flag={{flagcountry|Nazi Germany}}\n|desc=[[World War II]]: The cargo ship was bombed and sunk by aircraft off [[Norway]].<ref>{{csr|register=MSI|id=5605885|shipname=Leesee |accessdate=1 May 2012}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Modesta|1916|2}} \n|flag={{flag|United Kingdom|civil}}\n|desc=World War II: The cargo ship was torpedoed and sunk in the [[Atlantic Ocean]] ({{coord|33|40|N|63|10|W}}) by {{GS|U-108|1940|2}} ({{navy|Nazi Germany}}) with the loss of 18 of her 41 crew. Survivors were rescued by {{MV|Belgian Airman||2}} ({{flag|Belgium}}).<ref name=Modesta>{{cite web |url= http://uboat.net/allies/merchants/ships/1567.html |title=Modesta |publisher=Uboat |accessdate=23 February 2012}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Toba Maru||2}} \n|flag={{Flagcountry|Empire of Japan}}\n|desc=World War II: The cargo ship was torpedoed and sunk in the [[South China Sea]] north west of [[Luzon]], Philippines ({{coord|17|01|N|120|15|E}}) by {{USS|Spearfish|SS-190|6}} ({{navy|USA|1912}}).<ref name=Spearfish>{{cite DANFS |title=Saury |url= http://www.hazegray.org/danfs/submar/ss190.txt |accessdate=30 December 2011}}</ref> \n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{ship|Estonian cargo ship|Vahur||2}} \n|flag={{flag|Estonia}}\n|desc=World War II: The Estonian cargo ship, seized by the Soviet Union in 1940, was sunk in the Port of Leningrad by German aircraft.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.shipsnostalgia.com/guides/Soviet_Merchant_Marine_Losses_in_WW2 |title=Soviet Marine Losses in WWII |publisher=Shipnostalgia.com |accessdate=11 March 2016}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list end}}\n\n==26 April==\n{{shipwreck list begin |date=26 April 1942 |sort=}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Alcoa Partner||2}} \n|flag={{flag|United States|1912}}\n|desc=[[World War II]]: The cargo ship was torpedoed and sunk in the [[Caribbean Sea]] {{convert|80|nmi|km}} north west of [[Bonaire]] ({{coord|13|32|N|67|57|W}}) by {{GS|U-66|1940|2}} ({{navy|Nazi Germany}}) with the loss of ten of her 35 crew.<ref name=AP>{{cite web |url=http://uboat.net/allies/merchants/ships/1569.html |title=Alcoa Partner |publisher=Uboat |date=16 February 2011}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Aziza''\n|flag={{flag|Egypt|1922}}\n|desc=World War II: The sailing ship was shelled and sunk in the [[Mediterranean Sea]] off [[Mandatory Palestine|Palestine]] by {{GS|U-81|1941|2}} ({{navy|Nazi Germany}}).<ref name=Aziza>{{cite web |url=http://uboat.net/allies/merchants/ships/1568.html |title=Aziza |publisher=Uboat |accessdate=19 February 2012}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{USS|Sturtevant|DD-240|6}} \n|flag={{navy|United States|1912}}\n|desc=World War II: The {{sclass-|Clemson|destroyer}} struck a mine and sank in the [[Atlantic Ocean]] off [[Key West, Florida]] with the loss of 15 of her 130 crew. }}\n{{shipwreck list end}}\n\n==27 April==\n{{shipwreck list begin |date=27 April 1942 |sort=}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{HMS|Fitzroy|J04|6}} \n|flag={{navy|UK}}\n|desc=[[World War II]]: The [[minesweeper]] struck a [[naval mine|mine]] and sank in the [[North Sea]] off [[Great Yarmouth]], [[Norfolk]].<ref name=seekrieg194204/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Inga||2}} \n|flag={{flag|Denmark}}\n|desc=The cargo ship was wrecked on the South Horns Reef.<ref name=Jordan446>{{cite book |title=The world's merchant fleets, 1939 |first=Roger |last=Jordan |publisher=Chatham publishing |location=London |year=1999 |page=446 |isbn=1 86176 023 X}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{ship|Russian training ship|Svir||2}} \n|flag={{navy|Soviet Union}}\n|desc=World War II: The [[training ship]] was sunk in a [[Luftwaffe]] air raid on [[Leningrad]].<ref name=seekrieg194204/> }}\n{{shipwreck list end}}\n\n==28 April==\n{{shipwreck list begin |date=28 April 1942 |sort=}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Arundo||2}} \n|flag={{flag|Netherlands}}\n|desc=[[World War II]]: The tanker was torpedoed and sunk in the [[Atlantic Ocean]] {{convert|15|nmi|km}} south of the ''[[Ambrose Lightship]]'' ({{navy|United States|coast guard}}) ({{coord|40|10|N|73|44|W}}) by {{GS|U-136|1941|2}} ({{navy|Nazi Germany}}) with the loss of six of her 43 crew. Survivors were rescued by {{USS|Lea|DD-118|6}} ({{navy|USA|1912}}).<ref name=Arundo>{{cite web |url= http://uboat.net/allies/merchants/ships/1570.html |title=Arundo |publisher=Uboat |accessdate=29 February 2012}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Tatsufuku Maru||2}} \n|flag={{flagcountry|Empire of Japan}}\n|desc=World War II: The cargo ship was torpedoed and sunk in the [[South China Sea]] by {{USS|Seal|SS-183|6}} ({{navy|USA|1912}}).<ref name=Seal>{{cite DANFS |title=Seal |url= http://www.hazegray.org/danfs/submar/ss183.txt |accessdate=30 December 2011}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{HMS|West Dean}} \n|flag={{navy|United Kingdom}}\n|desc=World War II: The {{sclass2-|West|tugboat}} was bombed and sunk at [[Malta]].<ref>{{cite web |url= http://uboat.net/allies/warships/ship/7522.html |title=HMS West Dean of the Royal Navy |publisher=Uboat |accessdate=28 April 2013}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{USS|YP-77}} \n|flag={{navy|USA|1912}}\n|desc=World War II: The [[Yard patrol boat|yard patrol craft]] was sunk off the Atlantic Coast in a collision.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.ibiblio.org/hyperwar/USN/USN-Chron/USN-Chron-1942.html |title=Official Chronology of the US Navy in WWII |publisher=Ibiblio |accessdate=29 April 2014}}\n</ref> }}\n{{shipwreck list end}}\n\n==29 April==\n{{shipwreck list begin |date=29 April 1942 |sort=}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{ship|ST|Alliance||2}} \n|flag={{flag|United Kingdom|civil}}\n|desc=[[World War II]]: The tug struck a mine and sank in the [[Mediterranean Sea]] off [[Famagusta]], Cyprus ({{coord|35|09|N|33|56|E}}) with the loss of three of her ten crew.<ref name=Alliance>{{cite web |url= http://uboat.net/allies/merchants/ships/1571.html |title=Alliance |publisher=Uboat |accessdate=8 April 2012}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Curityba|1911|2}} \n|flag={{flagcountry|Nazi Germany}}\n|desc=World War II: The cargo ship was torpedoed and sunk by the Soviet submarine {{ship|Soviet submarine|M-171||2}} ({{navy|Soviet Union}}) off [[Vard\u00f8]], Norway. There were 22 killed and 34 survivors.<ref name=Huan/><ref>{{csr|register=MSI|id=5614525|shipname=Curityba |accessdate=24 March 2012}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''F-14-V'' \n|flag={{flag|Norway}}\n|desc=World War II: The fishing trawler was on board {{SS|Curityba|1911|2}} ({{flagcountry|Nazi Germany}}) and was lost when that ship was sunk.<ref name=seekrieg194204/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{ship|German landing craft|F 130||2}}  \n|flag={{navy|Nazi Germany}}\n|desc=World War II: The Type A ''[[Marinefahrprahm]]'' was damaged by a Soviet mine in the [[Black Sea]] and beached. Refloated, repaired and returned to service.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.soviet-empire.com/ussr/viewtopic.php?f=149&t=53917&sid=cf2e067f65c3cd13e8ea4c14698c3173 |title=Red Fleet,Black Sea |publisher=soviet Empire |accessdate=17 July 2017}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{MV|Harry G. Seidel||2}} \n|flag={{flag|Panama}}\n|desc=World War II: The tanker was torpedoed and sunk in the [[Caribbean Sea]] west of [[Trinidad]] by {{GS|U-66|1940|2}} ({{navy|Nazi Germany}}) with the loss of two of her 50 crew.<ref name=HGS>{{cite web |url=http://uboat.net/allies/merchants/ships/1574.html |title=Harry G. Seidel |publisher=Uboat |date=16 February 2011}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Mobiloil||2}} \n|flag={{flag|United States|1912}}\n|desc=World War II: The tanker was torpedoed and sunk in the [[Atlantic Ocean]] {{convert|350|nmi|km}} north east of the [[Turks and Caicos Islands]] ({{coord|26|10|N|66|15|W}}). All 52 crew were rescued by {{USS|PC-490}} ({{navy|USA|1912}}).<ref name=Mobiloil>{{cite web |url= http://uboat.net/allies/merchants/ships/1573.html |title=Mobiloil |publisher=Uboat |accessdate=23 February 2012}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''T-494'' \n|flag={{navy|Soviet Union}}\n|desc=World War II: The auxiliary minesweeper was sunk in the Black Sea by German aircraft. 20 crew were killed and 19 survived.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.navypedia.org/ships/russia/ru_cm_ii_ms.htm |title=auxiliary minesweepers of WWII, USSR |publisher=Navypedia |accessdate=13 April 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.kchf.ru/ship/tral/t494.htm |title=T-494 |publisher=www.kchf.ru |accessdate=8 October 2019}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{ship||Terpsithea|schooner|2}} \n|flag={{flag|United Kingdom|civil}}\n|desc=World War II: The schooner struck a mine and sank off Famagusta ({{coord|35|09|N|33|56|E}}). All crew survived.<ref name=Terpsithea>{{cite web |url= http://uboat.net/allies/merchants/ships/1572.html |title=Terpsithea |publisher=Uboat |accessdate=8 April 2012}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{HMS|Urge}} \n|flag={{navy|UK}}\n|desc=World War II: The [[British U-class submarine|U-class]] [[submarine]] was sunk in the [[Mediterranean Sea]] off Ra's al-Hilal, [[Italian Libya|Libya]] by a [[Fiat CR.42]] aircraft of the ''[[Regia Aeronautica]]''.}}\n{{shipwreck list end}}\n\n==30 April==\n{{shipwreck list begin |date=30 April 1942 |sort=}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Ashkhabad||2}} \n|flag={{flag|Soviet Union}}\n|desc=[[File:Ashkhabad shelled.jpg|thumb|right|''Ashkhabad'']][[World War II]]: The cargo ship was torpedoed and damaged in the [[Atlantic Ocean]] {{convert|18|nmi|km}} south of [[Cape Lookout (North Carolina)|Cape Lookout]], [[North Carolina]] ({{coord|34|19|N|76|31|W}}) by {{GS|U-402||2}} ({{navy|Nazi Germany}}). She was abandoned by her 47 crew, who were rescued by {{HMT|Lady Elsa|FY214|6}} ({{navy|United Kingdom}}). ''Ashkhabad'' was assessed as salvageable, and {{ship|ST|Relief||2}} ({{flag|United States|1912}}) was despatched to her aid, but she was scuttled by {{USS|Semmes|AG-24|6}} ({{navy|USA|1912}}) and {{HMT|St Zeno|FY280|6}} ({{navy|United Kingdom}}) as a hazard to navigation.<ref name=Ashkhabad>{{cite web |url= http://uboat.net/allies/merchants/ships/1577.html |title=Ashkhabad |publisher=Uboat |accessdate=20 March 2012}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{MV|Athelempress||2}} \n|flag={{flag|United Kingdom|civil}}\n|desc=World War II: The tanker was torpedoed and sunk in the Atlantic Ocean {{convert|180|nmi|km}} east of [[Barbados]] ({{coord|13|21|N|56|15|W}}) by {{GS|U-162|1941|2}} ({{navy|Nazi Germany}}) with the loss of three of her 50 crew. Survivors were rescued by {{MV|Atlantic|1925|2}} ({{flag|Norway}}).<ref name=Athelempress>{{cite web |url= http://uboat.net/allies/merchants/ships/1578.html |title=Athelempress |publisher=Uboat |accessdate=6 March 2012}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{MV|Bidevind||2}} \n|flag={{flag|Norway}}\n|desc=World War II: The 4,956-[[gross register ton]] [[cargo ship]] was [[torpedo]]ed and sunk in the [[Atlantic Ocean]] ({{coord|39|35|N|72|42|W}}) by the [[submarine]] {{GS|U-752||2}} ({{navy|Nazi Germany}}). All 36 crew survived. Her wreck lies in {{convert|190|ft|m|0}} of water at {{coord|39|48|57|N|072|46|07|W|name=''Bidevind''}}.<ref name=Bidenvind>{{cite web |url=http://www.warsailors.com/singleships/bidevind.html |title= M/S Bidevind |publisher=Warsailors |accessdate=9 January 2012}}</ref><ref>[https://njscuba.net/sites/chart_deep_sea.php#Bidevind njscuba.net ''Bidevind'']</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{HMS|Edinburgh|16|6}} \n|flag={{navy|United Kingdom}}\n|desc=World War II: [[Convoy QP 11]]: The {{sclass2-|Town|cruiser|||1936}} was torpedoed and damaged in the [[Barents Sea]] north of [[Murmansk]], Soviet Union ({{coord|73|09|N|32|45|E}}) by {{GS|U-456||2}} ({{navy|Nazi Germany}}). She was taken in tow, but was torpedoed and sunk in the [[Kola Peninsula|Kola Inlet]] on 2 May by {{ship|German destroyer|Z24||2}} ({{navy|Nazi Germany}}) with the loss of 58 of her 750 crew. Survivors were rescued by {{HMS|Gossamer|J63|6}} and {{HMS|Harrier|J71|6}} (both {{navy|UK}}).\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Federal|1901|2}} \n|flag={{flag|United States|1912}}\n|desc=World War II: The tanker was torpedoed and sunk in the Atlantic Ocean {{convert|5|nmi|km}} north of [[Gibara]], Cuba ({{coord|21|13|N|76|05|W}}) by {{GS|U-507||2}} ({{navy|Nazi Germany}}) with the loss of five of her 33 crew. Survivors were rescued by a Cuban fishing vessel or reached shore in their lifeboat.<ref name=Federal>{{cite web |url= http://uboat.net/allies/merchants/ships/1576.html |title=Federal |publisher=Uboat |accessdate=29 March 2012}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Taborfjell|1937|2}} \n|flag={{flag|Norway}}\n|desc=World War II: The cargo ship was torpedoed and sunk in the Atlantic Ocean {{convert|95|nmi|km}} off [[Cape Cod]], [[Massachusetts]], United States ({{coord|41|52|N|67|43|W}}) by {{GS|U-576||2}} ({{navy|Nazi Germany}}) with the loss of 17 of her 20 crew. Survivors were rescued by {{HMS|P552}} ({{navy|UK}}).<ref name=Taborfjell>{{cite web |url=http://www.warsailors.com/singleships/taborfjell.html |title=D/S Taborfjell |publisher=Warsailors |accessdate=8 February 2012}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Tsiokolvsky||2}} \n|flag={{flag|Soviet Union}}\n|desc=World War II: [[Convoy QP 11]]: The cargo ship was torpedoed and sunk in the North Sea by {{ship|German destroyer|Z24||2}} and {{ship|German destroyer|Z25||2}} (both {{navy|Nazi Germany}}).<ref name=seekrieg194204/> }}\n{{shipwreck list end}}\n\n==Unknown date==\n{{shipwreck list begin |date=Unknown date 1942 |sort=}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{MV|Chr. Knudsen||2}} \n|flag={{flag|Norway}}\n|desc=[[World War II]]: The cargo ship departed from [[New York City|New York]], United States for [[Cape Town]], South Africa on 8 April; no further trace. It is possible that she was torpedoed and sunk by {{GS|U-85|1941|2}} ({{navy|Nazi Germany}}) on 10 April with the loss of all 33 crew.<ref name=CK>{{cite web |url=http://www.warsailors.com/singleships/chrknudsen.html |title= M/S Chr. Knudsen |publisher=Warsailors |accessdate=12 January 2012}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item \n|ship={{HMS|LCA 211}} \n|flag={{navy|UK}}\n|desc=World War II: The [[landing craft assault]] was lost in April.<ref name=\"Navypedia\">{{cite web |url= http://www.navypedia.org/ships/uk/brit_aws_lcalcsm.htm |title=LCA Assault Landing Craft and LCS(M) Support Landing Craft, Royal Navy |publisher=Navypedia |accessdate=4 April 2017}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{HMS|LCM 38}} \n|flag={{navy|UK}}\n|desc=World War II: The [[landing craft mechanized]] was lost sometime in April.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.navypedia.org/ships/uk/brit_aws_lcm.htm |title=LCM) Landing Craft, Royal Navy |publisher=Navypedia |accessdate=6 April 2017}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''MMS 148''\n|flag={{navy|UK}}\n|desc=World War II: The incomplete {{sclass2-|MMS|minesweeper}} was scuttled on the stocks at the Rangoon Dockyard, Rangoon, Burma, sometime in March.<ref name=\"MMS class minesweepers, Royal Navy\">{{cite web |url=http://www.navypedia.org/ships/uk/brit_c_f_mms105.htm |title=MMS class minesweepers, Royal Navy |publisher=Navypedia |accessdate=30 March 2017}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''MMS 153''\n|flag={{navy|UK}}\n|desc=World War II: The incomplete {{sclass2-|MMS|minesweeper}} was scuttled on the stocks at the Irrawaddy Flotilla co. shipyard, Rangoon, Burma, sometime in March.<ref name=\"MMS class minesweepers, Royal Navy\">{{cite web |url=http://www.navypedia.org/ships/uk/brit_c_f_mms105.htm |title=MMS class minesweepers, Royal Navy |publisher=Navypedia |accessdate=30 March 2017}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\