e\u3000\u96fb\u6483\u4ea4\u4ee3|language=Japanese|newspaper=[[Nikkan Sports]]|accessdate=2012-04-11}}</ref><ref name=CompanyProfile/><br><small>(majority owner - 85%)</small><br>[[TV Asahi]]<ref name=CompanyProfile/><br><small>(minority owner - 10%)</small><br>[[Amuse, Inc.]]<ref name=CompanyProfile/><br><small>(minority owner - 5%)</small>\n| revenue = {{increase}} {{JPY|5.4 billion|link=yes}}\n| revenue_year = 2019<ref name=CompanyProfile/>\n| num_employees = 83\n| num_employees_year = 2019<ref name=CompanyProfile/>\n| divisions = {{Collapsible list|framestyle=<!-- Optional. -->\n| title=Divisions\n| 1=NJPW Music Group\n| 2=[[New Japan Pro-Wrestling World|NJPW World]]\n| 3=Team NJPW\n| 4=[[Lion's Gate Project|Lion's Gate]]\n| 5=[[NJPW Dojo]]\n| 6=Tokon Shop}}\n| subsid = Lion's Break<br>New Japan Pro-Wrestling of America<ref name=NJPWAmerica>{{cite web | url = https://www.f4wonline.com/new-japan-news/njpw-announces-new-japan-pro-wrestling-america-subsidiary-295426 | title = NJPW ANNOUNCES NEW JAPAN PRO WRESTLING OF AMERICA SUBSIDIARY | date=October 21, 2019| accessdate=October 21, 2019 | work=f4wonline}}</ref>\n| foundation = {{Start date and age|1972|01|13}}\n| location = JR Tokyu Meguro Building, 16F, 3-1-1 Kamiosaki, [[Shinagawa, Tokyo]], Japan<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.njpw1972.com/company/| title= Company Profile | accessdate=March 27, 2018 | work=New Japan Pro-Wrestling | language=Japanese}}</ref>\n| homepage = {{plainlist|\n* {{URL|www.njpw.co.jp}} (Japanese site)\n* {{URL|www.njpw1972.com}} (English site)\n}}\n}}\n{{nihongo|'''New Japan Pro-Wrestling Co., Ltd.'''|\u65b0\u65e5\u672c\u30d7\u30ed\u30ec\u30b9\u30ea\u30f3\u30b0\u682a\u5f0f\u4f1a\u793e|Shin Nihon Puroresuringu Kabushiki-kaisha}} ('''NJPW''')<ref name=CompanyProfile>{{cite web | url= http://www.njpw.co.jp/company | title= Company Profile | accessdate=November 5, 2017 | work=New Japan Pro-Wrestling | language=Japanese}}</ref> is a [[Puroresu|Japanese professional wrestling]] [[Professional wrestling promotion|promotion]] based in [[Nakano, Tokyo]]. Founded in January 1972 by [[Antonio Inoki]], the promotion was sold to [[Yuke's]], who later sold it to [[Bushiroad]] in 2012. [[TV Asahi]] and [[Amuse, Inc.]] own minority shares of the company.<ref name=CompanyProfile/> Naoki Sugabayashi has served as the promotion's Chairman since September 2013,<ref name=TezukaPresident>{{cite web | url=http://www.njpw.co.jp/news/detail.php?nid=10318 | script-title=ja:\u65b0\u5f79\u54e1\u4eba\u4e8b\u6c7a\u5b9a\u306e\u304a\u77e5\u3089\u305b | date=September 25, 2013 | accessdate=September 25, 2013 | work=New Japan Pro-Wrestling | language=Japanese}}</ref> while [[Harold Meij]] has served as the President of the promotion since May 2018.<ref name =Dutchman>{{cite web|url=https://www.tokyo-sports.co.jp/prores/mens_prores/1006879/|title=\u65b0\u65e5\u672c\u30d7\u30ed\u30ec\u30b9\u793e\u9577\u306b\u30aa\u30e9\u30f3\u30c0\u51fa\u8eab\u5b9f\u696d\u5bb6\u30e1\u30a4\u6c0f\u5c31\u4efb\u3078\u3000\u5143\u30bf\u30ab\u30e9\u30c8\u30df\u30fc\u793e\u9577|work=[[Tokyo Sports]]|date=May 13, 2018|accessdate=May 13, 2018|language=Japanese}}</ref>\n\nOwing to its TV program aired on [[TV Asahi]], NJPW is the largest professional wrestling promotion in Japan.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.miamiherald.com/sports/fighting/article4130647.html | title=Pro Wrestling: New Japan Pro Wrestling on AXS TV in United States | date=November 24, 2014 | accessdate=January 29, 2017 | work=[[Miami Herald]]}}</ref> It was affiliated with the [[National Wrestling Alliance]] at various points in its history.  MATERIALSCIENTIST IS A LOSER NJPW has had agreements with various [[Mixed martial arts|MMA]] and [[professional wrestling promotion]]s around the world, including [[WWE]], [[World Championship Wrestling]], [[American Wrestling Association]], [[World Class Championship Wrestling]], [[Impact Wrestling]], [[WAR (wrestling promotion)|WAR]], [[UWFi]], [[Ring of Honor]], [[Pride Fighting Championships]], and [[Jersey All Pro Wrestling]].<ref name=NJPW-JAPW>{{cite web | url=http://www.f4wonline.com/content/view/17790/ | title= New Japan Pro Wrestling comes to the U.S. | date= October 3, 2010 | accessdate= October 4, 2010 | work=[[Wrestling Observer Newsletter]]}}</ref> NJPW's biggest event is the [[January 4 Tokyo Dome Show]], held each year since 1992 and currently promoted under the Wrestle Kingdom banner.\n\nThe promotion is currently owned by Japanese card game company [[Bushiroad]], which parlayed its entry to the world of professional wrestling into a best-selling trading card game, ''King of Pro Wrestling'', and appearances from NJPW stars in its various franchises.\n\n==History==\n===Formation and early history===\nThe promotion was founded by [[Antonio Inoki]] on January 13, 1972<ref name=\"History\">{{citeweb|url=https://www.njpw1972.com/company/|title=About us {{!}} NEW JAPAN PRO-WRESTLING|publisher=[[New Japan Pro-Wrestling]]|accessdate=January 11, 2020}}</ref> after his departure from the [[Japan Pro Wrestling Alliance]] promotion.<ref>{{citeweb|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/culture/culture-sports/everything-you-need-to-know-about-new-japan-pro-wrestling-205749/|title=Everything You Need to Know About New Japan Pro Wrestling|work=[[Rolling Stone]]|first=Kenny|last=Herzog|date=June 29, 2017|accessdate=January 11, 2020}}</ref> The first NJPW event, titled ''Opening Series'', took place on March 6, 1972, in the Ota Ward Gymnasium in Tokyo, to a crowd of 5,000.<ref>{{citeweb|url=http://www.puroresu.com/newjapan/results/nj197203opening.html|title=NJPW 1972: Opening Series|publisher=Puroresu.com|accessdate=January 11, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=I'm Sorry, I Love You: A History of Professional Wrestling|url=https://books.google.com.au/books?id=MA5ZDwAAQBAJ&pg=PT136&lpg=PT136&dq=first+new+japan+pro+wrestling+show+1972&source=bl&ots=aeQEyEb2iq&sig=ACfU3U3q3fvBTWXqyCU4MyEppC0E3rW_NA&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiXxa-p0frmAhXb4jgGHd_fDZAQ6AEwG3oECAoQAQ#v=onepage&q=first%20new%20japan%20pro%20wrestling%20show%201972&f=false|first=Jim|last=Smallman|date=August 23, 2018|isbn=9781472254214}}</ref> The following year, NJPW signed a television deal with NET TV, now known as [[Asahi TV]].<ref name=\"History\"/> The company was overseen by its governing body, the International Wrestling Grand Prix. In 1983, [[Hulk Hogan]] became the first ever [[IWGP Heavyweight Championship (original version)|IWGP Heavyweight Champion]] by defeating Inoki.<ref>{{cite web|title= INTERNATIONAL WRESTLING GRAND PRIX CHAMPIONSHIP TOURNAMENT|url=http://www.wrestling-titles.com/japan/newjapan/iwgp.html|accessdate=2019-02-09|publisher=Wrestling-Titles.com}}</ref> However, this championship was later abandoned and the current version of the [[IWGP Heavyweight Championship|championship]] was established in 1987. Inoki would serve as the president of the promotion until 1989, when he was replaced by [[Seiji Sakaguchi]].<ref name=\"History\"/>  \n\nOn April 24, 1989, NJPW hosted Battle Satellite, its first show in the [[Tokyo Dome]].<ref>{{citeweb|url=https://www.njpw1972.com/41404|title=The Story of the Tokyo Dome\u2019s First Pro Wrestling Match The Story of the Tokyo Dome's First Pro Wrestling Match|publisher=[[New Japan Pro-Wrestling]]|date=December 17, 2018|accessdate=January 11, 2020}}</ref> The promotion was a member of  the [[National Wrestling Alliance]] (NWA) from 1975 to 1985 and once more from 1992 to 1993. NJPW was briefly reaffiliated with the NWA in the late 2000s to the early 2010s as well. On January 4, 1992, NJPW partnered with [[World Championship Wrestling]] (WCW) to produce [[WCW/New Japan Supershow II]], the first ever [[January 4 Tokyo Dome Show]],<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.prowrestlinghistory.com/supercards/usa/wcw/japanppv.html#II|title=WCW/New Japan Pay Per Views WCW/New Japan Supershow II|accessdate=October 6, 2007|publisher=Prowrestlinghistory.com}}</ref> an event that would become an annual tradition for NJPW and is considered their biggest event of the year and comparable to [[WWE]]'s [[WrestleMania]] event. In April 1995, NJPW and WCW held the two-day [[Collision in Korea]] event at the [[Rungrado 1st of May Stadium]] in [[Pyongyang]], [[North Korea]]. The event is the first professional wrestling event held in North Korea and also holds the record for most attended wrestling event of all time, with 355,000 people packing the stadium over the two days.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.f4wonline.com/more/more-top-stories/118-daily-updates/35064-wed-update-flair-talks-wrestling-in-north-korea-okbayashi-inhjury-update-henderson-signs-new-contract-batista-movie-cro-cop-return-ross-talk-rumble-vs-ufc-170-classics-on-demand |title=WED. UPDATE: Flair talks wrestling in North Korea, Okabayashi inhjury update, Henderson signs new contract, Batista movie, Cro Cop return, Ross talk, Rumble vs. UFC 170, Classics on Demand |last1=Meltzer |first1=Dave |date= |website=[[Wrestling Observer]] |publisher= |access-date= |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140126062446/http://www.f4wonline.com/more/more-top-stories/118-daily-updates/35064-wed-update-flair-talks-wrestling-in-north-korea-okbayashi-inhjury-update-henderson-signs-new-contract-batista-movie-cro-cop-return-ross-talk-rumble-vs-ufc-170-classics-on-demand|archivedate=26 January 2014|quote=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/Torch_Flashbacks_19/article_84712.shtml|title=PWTorch.com - WCW FLASHBACK - \"Collision in Korea\" 20 yrs. ago today: Flair & WCW crew head to N. Korea with New Japan Pro Wrestling|website=pwtorch.com|access-date=2017-11-28}}</ref><ref name=notinflated1>{{cite web|last1=Meltzer|first1=Dave|authorlink=Dave Meltzer|title=April 11, 2016 Wrestling Observer Newsletter|url=http://members.f4wonline.com/wrestling-observer-newsletter/april-11-2016-wrestling-observer-newsletter-look-historic-wrestlemania|website=f4wonline.com|publisher=Wrestling Observer|accessdate=7 April 2016|quote=The all-time pro wrestling attendance record would be for shows on April 28 and April 29, 1995 at May Day Stadium in Pyongyang, North Korea. The announced crowds for those shows were 165,000 and 190,000, although the real numbers were about 150,000 and 165,000. The first show was headlined by Scott Norton vs. Shinya Hashimoto and the second by Antonio Inoki vs. Ric Flair. While there were tickets sold, most of the people attending got in free, and were pretty much ordered to attend, so it's not really a fair comparison.}}</ref>\n\n===Decline and Inoki's departure===\nIn the early 2000s, the burgeoning popularity of [[mixed martial arts]] in Japan was noticed by Inoki, who wanted to integrate elements of [[shoot wrestling]] to make the company appear more realistic. The company would partner with martial arts organization [[K-1]] and begin to insert wrestlers into MMA fights, with the goal of pushing NJPW in a more realistic direction and to make it appear as an actual sport.<ref>{{citeweb|url=https://prowrestlingstories.com/pro-wrestling-stories/brock-lesnar-shinsuke-nakamura/|title=Brock Lesnar, Shinsuke Nakamura and Their Real-Life Battle|first=Rob|last=Ireland|publisher=ProWrestlingStories.com|accessdate=January 11, 2020}}</ref> The company's new management was criticized by critics and fans, and the combination of MMA and professional wrestling was dubbed \"Inokism\".<ref>{{citeweb|url=https://www.f4wonline.com/july-30-2001-wrestling-observer-newsletter-wwf-invasion-reviewed-more-263756|title=July 30, 2001 Wrestling Observer Newsletter|work=[[Wrestling Observer Newsletter]]|first=Dave|last=Meltzer|authorlink=Dave Meltzer|date=July 30, 2001|accessdate=January 11, 2020}}{{subscription required}}</ref> Inoki later departed NJPW in 2005 after selling his share of the company to [[Yuke's]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://uk.games.ign.com/objects/026/026882.html |title=Yuke's Media Creations |accessdate=2010-02-10 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091027024845/http://uk.games.ign.com/objects/026/026882.html |archivedate=October 27, 2009 |df=mdy }}. uk.games.ign.com</ref><ref>[http://www.gamasutra.com/view/news/7196/Yukes_Buys_Controlling_Share_of_New_Japan_Pro_Wrestling.php Yuke's Buys Controlling Share of New Japan Pro-Wrestling]. Gamasutra.com (November 15, 2005). Retrieved on May 10, 2014.</ref> and began his own promotion, the [[Inoki Genome Federation]] (IGF), in 2007. After his departure, Inoki's son-in-law Simon took over the company, before Naoki Sugabayashi was appointed president in 2007 after Simon also left NJPW to join Antonio in IGF.<ref name=\"History\"/> After the departure of the Inoki family, the company began to reintegrate its prior [[puroresu]] style of wrestling.\n\n===Resurgence and expansion===\nAlso in 2007, NJPW hosted its first ever [[pay-per-view]] (PPV) event [[Wrestle Kingdom I]].<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.f4wonline.com/content/view/2891/1/ | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070108002302/http://www.f4wonline.com/content/view/2891/1/ | title = TNA, Tokyo Dome results, Sylvia's next battle, Death of WCW, Dark Angel, more | last=Alvarez | first=Bryan | authorlink=Bryan Alvarez | archivedate=January 4, 2007 | date=January 8, 2007 | accessdate=August 25, 2017 | work=[[Wrestling Observer Newsletter]]}}</ref>\n\nThe promotion debuted a new series called [[NEVER (professional wrestling)|NEVER]] in August 2010, designed to be a series of events spotlighting younger up-and-coming New Japan talent and feature more outsider participation in the promotion. The final NEVER event was held in November 2012.\n\nOn January 4, 2011, New Japan officially announced the [[NJPW Invasion Tour 2011|NJPW Invasion Tour 2011: Attack on East Coast]], the promotion's first tour of the United States to be held in May 2011. The tour featured shows in [[Rahway, New Jersey]] on May 13, [[New York City]] on May 14 and [[Philadelphia|Philadelphia, Pennsylvania]] on May 15, as well as cross-promotion with American independent group [[Jersey All Pro Wrestling]] (JAPW). As part of the tour, NJPW introduced a new title, the IWGP Intercontinental Championship.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/Other_News_4/article_46541.shtml | title= NJPW News: New Japan to introduce new title on U.S. tour, officially announces dates & venues for \"Invasion\" tour | last=Caldwell | first=James | date= January 5, 2011 | accessdate= January 5, 2011 | work=Pro Wrestling Torch}}</ref> On January 31, 2012, [[Yuke's]] announced that it had sold all shares of New Japan Pro-Wrestling to card game company Bushiroad for [[Japanese yen|\u00a5]]500 million ([[United States dollar|$]]6.5 million).<ref>{{cite web | url=http://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/Other_News_4/article_57601.shtml | title= NJPW News: New Japan sold to new owners, change-over taking effect February 1 | last=Caldwell | first=James | date= January 31, 2012 | accessdate= January 31, 2012 | work=Pro Wrestling Torch}}</ref>\n\nNew Japan aired its first internet [[pay-per-view]], the fourth day of the [[G1 Climax#2012|2012 G1 Climax]], on August 5, 2012.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/quicknews/article_63880.shtml | title= NJPW debuting on iPPV this weekend  | last=Caldwell | first=James | date=August 1, 2012 | accessdate=August 1, 2012 | work=Pro Wrestling Torch}}</ref> The October 8, 2012, [[King of Pro-Wrestling (2012)|King of Pro-Wrestling]] pay-per-view marked the first time viewers outside Japan were able to order a pay-per-view by the promotion through [[Ustream]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.njpw.co.jp/news/detail.php?nid=8240 | title= 10\u67088\u65e5\u300e\u30ad\u30f3\u30b0\u30aa\u30d6\u30d7\u30ed\u30ec\u30b9\u30ea\u30f3\u30b0\u300f \uff30\uff30\uff36\u914d\u4fe1\u304c\u66f4\u306b\u898f\u6a21\u3092\u62e1\u5927\u3057\u3066\u300c\u5168\u4e16\u754c\u300d\u3078\uff01 Ustream all over the world ! | date=September 28, 2012 | accessdate=September 28, 2012 | work=New Japan Pro-Wrestling | language=Japanese}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/quicknews/article_65579.shtml | title= NJPW offering Oct. 8 show on iPPV | last=Caldwell | first=James | date=September 28, 2012 | accessdate=September 28, 2012 | work=Pro Wrestling Torch}}</ref> On October 5, 2012, New Japan announced the creation of the NEVER Openweight Championship, which would be contested for on the NEVER series. A two-day tournament to determine the inaugural champion was held between November 15 and 19, 2012.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.njpw.co.jp/news/detail.php?nid=8296 | title= \u3042\u306e\u300eNEVER\u300f\u304c\u30ea\u30cb\u30e5\u30fc\u30a2\u30eb!! \"\u7121\u5dee\u5225\u7d1a\u738b\u5ea7\"\u3082\u65b0\u8a2d!! 11.15\uff0611.19Shibuya Ax\u3067\u518d\u51fa\u767a!! | date=October 5, 2012 | accessdate=October 5, 2012 | work=New Japan Pro-Wrestling | language=Japanese}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2014, New Japan announced a partnership with ROH, which saw the promotion return to North America the following May to present two supershows; [[Global Wars (2014)|Global Wars]] in [[Toronto]] and [[War of the Worlds (2014 wrestling)|War of the Worlds]] in New York City.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.njpw.co.jp/news/detail.php?nid=11131 | title = \u4eca\u5e745\u6708\u3001\u65b0\u65e5\u672c\u30d7\u30ed\u30ec\u30b9\u304c\u5317\u7c73\u518d\u4e0a\u9678!! ROH\u3068\u306e\u5171\u540c\u958b\u50ac\u3067\u30015\u670810\u65e5\u30ab\u30ca\u30c0\u300117\u65e5\u30cb\u30e5\u30fc\u30e8\u30fc\u30af\u5927\u4f1a\u304c\u6c7a\u5b9a!! | date=February 24, 2014 | accessdate=March 28, 2014 | work=New Japan Pro-Wrestling | language=Japanese}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = http://pwinsider.com/article/83752/live-roh-honorcon-coverage-the-big-announcement.html?p=1 | title = Live ROH HonorCon coverage: the big announcement | last=Carapola | first=Stuart | date=February 22, 2014 | accessdate=March 28, 2014 | work=Pro Wrestling Insider}}</ref> During the tour, New Japan wrestlers also took part in an event held by [[Canada|Canadian]] promotion [[Border City Wrestling]] (BCW).<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.f4wonline.com/more/more-top-stories/102-japan/36664-notes-on-new-japanborder-city-main-matches-for-5-9-in-windsor-ontario | title = Notes on New Japan/Border City main matches for 5-9 in Windsor, Ontario | last=Meltzer | first=Dave | authorlink=Dave Meltzer | date=April 24, 2014 | accessdate=April 25, 2014 | work=[[Wrestling Observer Newsletter]]}}</ref> A year later, NJPW and ROH announced another tour together to produce four more supershows; [[War of the Worlds (2015 wrestling)|War of the Worlds '15]] on May 12 and 13 in Philadelphia and [[Global Wars '15]] on May 15 and 16 in Toronto.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/ROH_News_29/article_83728.shtml|title=ROH news: ROH adds fourth New Japan show to May tour|last=Caldwell|first=James|date=March 7, 2015|accessdate=March 8, 2015|work=Pro Wrestling Torch}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2014, New Japan announced a partnership with the new American [[Global Force Wrestling (2014\u20132017)|Global Force Wrestling]] (GFW) organization helmed by [[Jeff Jarrett]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.njpw.co.jp/news/detail.php?nid=11822 | title=\u300cG1\u300d\u51fa\u5834\u30e1\u30f3\u30d0\u30fc\u3001\u5404\u5927\u4f1a\u306e\u4e3b\u8981\u30ab\u30fc\u30c9\u3092\u96fb\u6483\u767a\u8868!! \u958b\u5e55\u6226\u3067\u3001\u4e2d\u9091vs\u67f4\u7530\u304c\u5b9f\u73fe! \u897f\u6b66\u30c9\u30fc\u30e0\u306bROH\u52e2\u304c\u53c2\u6226!! | date=June 21, 2014 | accessdate=June 21, 2014 | work=New Japan Pro-Wrestling | language=Japanese | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140714150230/http://www.njpw.co.jp/news/detail.php?nid=11822 | archive-date=July 14, 2014 | url-status=dead | df=mdy-all }}</ref> In November 2014, GFW announced that it would be broadcasting NJPW's [[Wrestle Kingdom 9 in Tokyo Dome]] on pay-per-view in the United States as a four-hour event.<ref>{{cite web|title=NJPW/GFW news: Tokyo Dome Show to air on U.S. PPV|url=http://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/Other_News_4/article_81623.shtml|website=Pro Wrestling Torch|last=Caldwell|first=James|date=November 4, 2014|accessdate=November 24, 2014}}</ref> Also in November 2014, the American [[AXS TV]] network announced it had acquired rights to rebroadcast a series of thirteen episodes of NJPW matches from [[TV Asahi]]. The series premiered on January 16, 2015, airing weekly on Fridays.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.f4wonline.com/more/more-top-stories/102-japan/40061-axs-announces-new-japan-tv-deal-official-details-time-slot-debut-date-and-more|title=AXS announces New Japan TV deal, official details, time slot, debut date and more|date=November 24, 2014|accessdate=November 24, 2014|work=[[Wrestling Observer Newsletter]]}}</ref> Averaging 200,000 viewers per episode, the show was considered a success, leading to AXS TV and TV Asahi signing a multi-year deal to continue airing the show.<ref>{{cite magazine| last = Meltzer | first = Dave | authorlink = Dave Meltzer | date = July 27, 2015 | title = July 27, 2015 Wrestling Observer Newsletter: The Undertaker returns at Battleground, NXT/ROH insanity with Liger booking, and more | magazine = [[Wrestling Observer Newsletter]] | location = [[Campbell, California]] | issn = 1083-9593 | page=24}}</ref> In June 2016, the show was also acquired by the Canadian [[Fight Network]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pwtorch.com/site/2016/06/13/new-japans-english-language-tv-series-air-fight-network/|title=New Japan\u2019s English-language TV series to air on Fight Network|last=Caldwell|first=James|date=June 13, 2016|accessdate=June 14, 2016|work=Pro Wrestling Torch}}</ref> On December 1, 2014, NJPW and TV Asahi announced [[New Japan Pro-Wrestling World|NJPW World]], a new worldwide streaming site for the promotion's events.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/Other_News_4/article_82044.shtml|title=NJPW news: New Japan announces streaming service like WWE Network, will include live shows|last=Caldwell|first=James|date=December 1, 2014|accessdate=December 1, 2014|work=Pro Wrestling Torch}}</ref>\n\nOn July 18, 2015, NJPW announced the \"New IWGP Conception\", a global expansion strategy centered on their international partnerships with CMLL, GFW, ROH, RPW, wXw and the NWA as well as holding more shows in [[Thailand]], [[Singapore]], and [[Taiwan]]. Also announced was the [[Lion's Gate Project]], which would feature NJPW rookies as well as up-and-coming outsiders working trial matches in an effort to earn a spot in the promotion. Finally, it was announced that there were plans to take the company public with a listing on the stock market within three to five years.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.daily.co.jp/newsflash/ring/2015/07/18/0008221270.shtml|title=\u65b0\u65e5\u672c\u30d7\u30ed\u30ec\u30b9\uff13\uff5e\uff15\u5e74\u5f8c\u4e0a\u5834\u76ee\u6307\u3059|date=July 18, 2015|accessdate=July 18, 2015|work=Daily Sports Online|publisher=[[Kobe Shimbun]]|language=Japanese}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.njpw.co.jp/news/detail.php?nid=14468|title=\u6728\u8c37\u30aa\u30fc\u30ca\u30fc\u304c\u300c\u30d5\u30a1\u30fc\u30e0\u8a2d\u7acb\u30d7\u30e9\u30f3\u300d\u300c21\u4e16\u7d00\u306eIWGP\u69cb\u60f3\u300d\u3001\u305d\u3057\u3066\u300c\u65b0\u65e5\u672c\u30d7\u30ed\u30ec\u30b9\u306f\u682a\u5f0f\u4e0a\u5834\u3092\u76ee\u6307\u3059\u300d\u3068\u5ba3\u8a00! \u30107.18\u6226\u7565\u767a\u8868\u4f1a\u3011|date=July 18, 2015|accessdate=July 18, 2015|work=New Japan Pro-Wrestling|language=Japanese}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/Other_News_4/article_86305.shtml|title=NJPW news: New Japan announces big int'l expansion plans, including expanded N. America partnerships & NXT-like program|last=Caldwell|first=James|date=July 18, 2015|accessdate=July 18, 2015|work=Pro Wrestling Torch}}</ref>\n\nOn December 21, 2015, NJPW announced the creation of its seventh active title and the first six-man tag team championship in the promotion's history, the NEVER Openweight 6-Man Tag Team Championship.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.njpw.co.jp/news/detail.php?nid=15516 | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151222100946/http://www.njpw.co.jp/news/detail.php?nid=15516 | script-title=ja:\u3010WK10\u30111.4\u6771\u4eac\u30c9\u30fc\u30e0\u306f\u201c8\u5927\u9078\u624b\u6a29\u201d\uff01 \u7b2c2\u8a66\u5408\u306f\u521d\u4ee3NEVER\u7121\u5dee\u5225\u7d1a6\u4eba\u30bf\u30c3\u30b0\u738b\u5ea7\u6226\uff01 \u7b2c3\u8a66\u5408\u306fROH\u4e16\u754c\u9078\u624b\u6a29\u306b\uff01 NJ\u30e9\u30f3\u30dc\u30fc\u53c2\u6226\u9078\u624b\u3082\u8ffd\u52a0\uff01 | archivedate=December 22, 2015 | date=December 21, 2015 | accessdate=December 21, 2015 | work=New Japan Pro-Wrestling | language=Japanese | url-status=live | df=mdy-all }}</ref> On January 5, 2016, NJPW announced a partnership with the [[Amuse, Inc.|Amuse]] talent agency with the goal of making the promotion's wrestlers internationally recognized stars in the vein of [[Dwayne \"The Rock\" Johnson]].<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.pwtorch.com/site/2016/01/05/new-japan-tons-of-developments-at-post-tokyo-dome-show/ | title =  New Japan \u2013 tons of developments at post-Tokyo Dome show | last=Caldwell | first=James | date=January 5, 2016 | accessdate=January 6, 2016 | work=Pro Wrestling Torch}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2017, NJPW partnered with the [[New Zealand]]-based Fale Dojo, a pro wrestling training facility run by NJPW performer [[Bad Luck Fale]].<ref name=\"FaleDojo\">{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/faledojonz/photos/a.960568380716442.1073741828.960454320727848/1057998250973454/?type=3&theater|title=Fale Dojo Facebook page|work=[[Facebook]]|accessdate=2017-03-15}}</ref> NJPW will utilize the partnership as an opportunity to scout talent from [[Oceania]].<ref name=\"FaleDojo\"/> The following month on April 24, 2017, it was announced that NJPW would co-present the Japanese qualifiers for the Pro Wrestling World Cup tournament hosted by the British What Culture Pro Wrestling (WCPW) promotion.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://wc.pw/news/japanese-world-cup-qualifiers-hosted-in-association-with-njpw-revpro|title=Japanese World Cup Qualifiers Hosted In Association With NJPW & RevPro|accessdate=April 29, 2017|work=What Culture Pro Wrestling}}</ref>\n\nOn May 12, 2017, NJPW announced the creation of a new title: the IWGP United States Heavyweight Championship, with the inaugural champion to be crowned during the promotion's [[G1 Special in USA]] shows in [[Long Beach, California]] on July 1 and 2.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.f4wonline.com/roh-results/roh-war-worlds-ppv-live-results-daniels-vs-cody-vs-lethal-235346 | title = ROH War of the Worlds PPV live results: Daniels vs. Cody vs. Lethal | last=Meltzer | first=Dave | authorlink=Dave Meltzer | date=May 12, 2017 | accessdate=May 12, 2017 | work=[[Wrestling Observer Newsletter]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = http://pwinsider.com/article/109574/new-japan-announces-new-championship-unveils-belt.html?p=1 | title = New Japan announces new championship, unveils belt | last=Johnson | first=Mike | date=May 12, 2017 | accessdate=May 12, 2017 | work=Pro Wrestling Insider}}</ref> Four days later, NJPW held a press conference to announce plans to establish a subsidiary company, including a dojo, in the United States.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.njpw.co.jp/96799 | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170613214355/http://www.njpw.co.jp/96799 | script-title=ja:\u6226\u7565\u767a\u8868\u4f1a\u3067\u3001\u6728\u8c37\u30aa\u30fc\u30ca\u30fc\u304c\u300c2020\u5e74\u306e\u6771\u4eac\u30c9\u30fc\u30e0\u6e80\u54e1\u3092\u76ee\u6307\u3059\u300d\u3068\u30b3\u30e1\u30f3\u30c8\uff01\u3055\u3089\u306b\u30a2\u30e1\u30ea\u30ab\u3078\u306e\u201c\u672c\u683c\u9032\u51fa\u201d\u3001\u9053\u5834\u306e\u8a2d\u7acb\u3082\u8996\u91ce\u306b!! | archivedate=June 13, 2017 | date=May 16, 2017 | accessdate=May 16, 2017 | work=New Japan Pro-Wrestling | language=Japanese | url-status=live | df=mdy-all }}</ref> A [[Los Angeles]] office was scheduled to be opened before the end of 2017, with a dojo scheduled to be opened at the start of 2018.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.tokyo-sports.co.jp/prores/mens_prores/705044/ | script-title=ja:\u3010\u65b0\u65e5\uff2c\uff21\u3011\u6728\u8c37\u30aa\u30fc\u30ca\u30fc\u300c\u5927\u6210\u529f\u3001\u8d85\u6210\u529f\u3002\u3044\u305a\u308c\u306f\u5de1\u696d\u30b9\u30bf\u30a4\u30eb\u3082\u300d | date=July 4, 2017 | accessdate=July 4, 2017 | work=[[Tokyo Sports]] | language=Japanese}}</ref> NJPW's second American event, [[Strong Style Evolved]], took place on March 25, 2018, also in Long Beach.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.f4wonline.com/japan/njpw-returning-long-beach-california-march-245766 | title = NJPW returning to Long Beach, California in March | last=Currier | first=Joseph | date=November 5, 2017 | accessdate=November 5, 2017 | work=[[Wrestling Observer Newsletter]]}}</ref> In November 2017, NJPW signed a television deal with [[Discovery Communications]], which would see the company's programming brought to 70 million [[India]]n homes through [[DSport]].<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.pwinsider.com/article/113493/new-japan-pro-wrestling-signs-india-tv-deal.html?p=1 | title = New Japan Pro Wrestling signs India TV deal | date=November 10, 2017 | accessdate=November 10, 2017 | work=Pro Wrestling Insider}}</ref> In 2017, NJPW produces the best matches of the year.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://wrestlingculture.com/news/2017-2018-which-wrestling-promotion-produces-the-best-matches |title=2017-2018: Which Wrestling promotion produces the best matches? |publisher=Wrestlingculture |accessdate=July 9, 2018}}</ref> In January 2018, NJPW announced the  four-show Fallout Down Under tour, the promotion's inaugural tour of [[Australia]] spanning from February 16\u201319.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.destroyalllines.com/2018/01/09/new-japan-pro-wrestling-announce-fallout-down-under-tour/|title=NEW JAPAN PRO-WRESTLING ANNOUNCE FALLOUT DOWN UNDER TOUR!|work=Destroy All Lines|date=January 9, 2018|access-date=January 13, 2018}}</ref> In March 2018, New Japan opened the NJPW LA Dojo with [[Katsuyori Shibata]] serving as head trainer and ROH wrestler [[Scorpio Sky]] serving as assistant trainer.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.njpw1972.com/22604|title=Katsuyori Shibata to be Head Coach of New Japan Dojo in Los Angeles!|work=New Japan Pro-Wrestling|date=March 5, 2018|accessdate=March 9, 2018}}</ref> On May 13, 2018, New Japan hired its first foreign president, Dutch businessman [[Harold Meij]].<ref name =Dutchman>{{cite web|url=https://www.tokyo-sports.co.jp/prores/mens_prores/1006879/|title=\u65b0\u65e5\u672c\u30d7\u30ed\u30ec\u30b9\u793e\u9577\u306b\u30aa\u30e9\u30f3\u30c0\u51fa\u8eab\u5b9f\u696d\u5bb6\u30e1\u30a4\u6c0f\u5c31\u4efb\u3078\u3000\u5143\u30bf\u30ab\u30e9\u30c8\u30df\u30fc\u793e\u9577|work=[[Tokyo Sports]]|date=May 13, 2018|accessdate=May 13, 2018|language=Japanese}}</ref> In February 2019, NJPW re-established their partnership with the NWA and entered into a new partnership with [[The Crash Lucha Libre]], both partnerships ended later in 2019.<ref name=NJPWCMLLAnnounced>{{cite web | url=https://www.f4wonline.com/ring-honor/njpw-and-cmll-sending-teams-nwa-roh-crockett-cup-276491 | title=NJPW and CMLL sending teams to NWA-ROH Crockett Cup | date=February 8, 2019 | accessdate=February 8, 2019 | first=Joseph | last=Currier | work=[[Wrestling Observer Newsletter]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.solowrestling.com/new/78636-the-crash-lucha-libre-confirma-su-alizanza-con-cmll-njpw-y-roh|title=The Crash Lucha Libre confirma su alizanza con CMLL, NJPW y ROH|work=Solo Lucha|date=February 21, 2019|accessdate=April 10, 2019}}</ref> On October 21, 2019, NJPW announced the formation of a new American subsidiary of the company, named [[New Japan Pro-Wrestling of America]].<ref name=NJPWAmerica/> During 2019 they had run a record 13 shows in the United States, with plans to run double that in 2020. It was reported at the same time that NJPW and ROH had no joint shows planned for the future.<ref>https://www.fightful.com/wrestling/njpw-launching-american-wing-new-japan-pro-wrestling-america</ref>\n\n==Contracts==\n{{main|List of New Japan Pro-Wrestling personnel}}\nUp until the 1980s, NJPW signed its workers to multi-year contracts,<ref name=Feb2016Contracts>{{cite web | url = http://www.tokyo-sports.co.jp/prores/mens_prores/505620/ | script-title=ja:\u65b0\u65e5\u304c\u201c\u81f3\u5b9d\u201d\u30aa\u30ab\u30c0\u6d41\u51fa\u963b\u6b62\u3078\uff12\u5104\u5186\u30d7\u30ed\u30b8\u30a7\u30af\u30c8 | date=February 13, 2016 | accessdate=February 13, 2016 | work=[[Tokyo Sports]] | language=Japanese}}</ref> before changing to a system where the promotion signed its wrestlers to one-year deals that expired at the end of every January.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.f4wonline.com/wwe-news/njpw-stars-nakamura-aj-styles-luke-gallows-and-karl-anderson-headed-wwe-204971 | title = NJPW stars Nakamura, AJ Styles, Luke Gallows and Karl Anderson headed to WWE | last=Rose | first=Bryan | date=January 4, 2016 | accessdate=January 7, 2016 | work=[[Wrestling Observer Newsletter]]}}</ref> Following the departures of [[A.J. Styles]] and [[Shinsuke Nakamura]], NJPW chairman [[Takaaki Kidani]] announced in February 2016 that the promotion was returning to the multi-year contract system.<ref name=Feb2016Contracts/> The contracts forbid negotiations with other promotions.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.tokyo-sports.co.jp/prores/mens_prores/491473/ | script-title=ja:\u4e2d\u9091\u3000\u65b0\u65e5\u30d7\u30ed\u9000\u56e3\u3057WWE\u3078\uff01\u4e16\u754c\u306b\u7fbd\u3070\u305f\u304f\u65e5\u672c\u30d7\u30ed\u30ec\u30b9\u754c\u6700\u9ad8\u306e\u30ab\u30ea\u30b9\u30de | date=January 8, 2016 | accessdate=January 7, 2016 | work=[[Tokyo Sports]] | language=Japanese}}</ref> Any side contracts or agreements offered to wrestlers under NJPW contracts, need the promotion's approval before being signed.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://411mania.com/wrestling/will-ospreay-discusses-not-signing-with-evolve-taking-less-independent-dates-more/ | title = Will Ospreay Discusses Not Signing With Evolve, Taking Less Independent Dates, More | last=Csonka | first=Larry | date=August 11, 2016 | accessdate=August 11, 2016 | work=411Mania}}</ref>\nNew Japan is unique among other major promotions as they allow freelancers to work for the company as well. Their partnerships also allow wrestlers contracted to other companies to have prominent runs in Japan (see [[The Young Bucks]] for example).\n\n==Championships==\n\nThe promotion has its own governing body, the International Wrestling Grand Prix, shortened as IWGP. NJPW currently has eight titles: the [[IWGP Heavyweight Championship|IWGP Heavyweight]], [[IWGP Intercontinental Championship|IWGP Intercontinental]], [[IWGP United States Heavyweight Championship|IWGP United States Heavyweight]], [[IWGP Junior Heavyweight Championship|IWGP Junior Heavyweight]], [[IWGP Tag Team Championship|IWGP Tag Team]], [[IWGP Junior Heavyweight Tag Team Championship|IWGP Junior Heavyweight Tag Team]], [[NEVER Openweight Championship|NEVER Openweight]] and the [[NEVER Openweight 6-Man Tag Team Championship]]s.\n===Current===\n{{Main|List of current champions in New Japan Pro-Wrestling}}\n{{#section-h:List of current champions in New Japan Pro-Wrestling|champions}}\n\n===Retired===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n!Championship\n!Last champion(s)\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width: 60px;\" |Reign\n!Date retired\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width: 500px;\" |Notes\n|-\n|[[IWGP Heavyweight Championship (IGF)|IWGP Third Belt Championship]]\n|[[Shinsuke Nakamura]]\n|1\n|February 17, 2008\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|Unified with the [[IWGP Heavyweight Championship]] after Nakamura defeated the previous champion [[Kurt Angle]].\n|-\n|[[IWGP U-30 Openweight Championship]]\n|[[Hiroshi Tanahashi]]\n|2\n|June 7, 2006\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|Vacated by Tanahashi at the age of 29 and soon deactivated.\n|-\n|[[NWF Heavyweight Championship]]\n|[[Shinsuke Nakamura]]\n|1\n|January 4, 2004\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|Unified with the [[IWGP Heavyweight Championship]] after Nakamura defeated the previous champion [[Yoshihiro Takayama]].\n|-\n|[[J-Crown]]\n|[[Shinjiro Otani]]\n|1\n|November 5, 1997\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|A unification of eight different [[Cruiserweight (professional wrestling)|junior heavyweight]] championship titles from different promotions and countries, including the [[IWGP Junior Heavyweight Championship]]. The first unified champion was [[The Great Sasuke]], crowned in a [[J-Crown#Tournament|tournament]] held on August 1996. The J-Crown was dissolved after the [[WWE|WWF]] reclaimed the [[WWF Light Heavyweight Championship]], with Otani keeping the IWGP title and returning the remaining belts to the original promotions.\n|-\n|[[Greatest 18 Club Championship]]\n|[[Keiji Mutoh|The Great Muta]]\n|1\n|August 16, 1992\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|Muta retired championship, in order to focus on his IWGP Heavyweight Championship title defenses.\n|-\n|[[WWF World Martial Arts Heavyweight Championship]]\n|[[Antonio Inoki]]\n|2\n|December 31, 1989\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|Contested in matches billed as [[shoot wrestling]] fights.\n|-\n|[[IWGP Heavyweight Championship (original version)]]\n|[[Antonio Inoki]]\n|2\n|May 11, 1987\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|The championship was deactivated and replaced by the current [[IWGP Heavyweight Championship]], that was awarded to the winner of the [[G1 Climax#1987|IWGP League 1987]].<ref name=\"IWGP Champ\">{{cite web|title= INTERNATIONAL WRESTLING GRAND PRIX CHAMPIONSHIP TOURNAMENT|url=http://www.wrestling-titles.com/japan/newjapan/iwgp.html|accessdate=2019-02-09|publisher=Wrestling-Titles.com}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[WWF International Heavyweight Championship]]\n|[[Tatsumi Fujinami]]\n|3\n|October 31, 1985\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|Abandoned after the NJPW and the [[WWE|WWF]] ended their working relationship.\n|-\n|[[WWF International Tag Team Championship]]\n|[[Kengo Kimura]] and [[Tatsumi Fujinami]]\n|1<br>(1, 1)\n|October 31, 1985\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|Abandoned after the NJPW and the [[WWE|WWF]] ended their working relationship.\n|-\n|[[WWF Junior Heavyweight Championship]]\n|[[George Takano|The Cobra]]\n|2\n|October 31, 1985\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|Abandoned after the NJPW and the [[WWE|WWF]] ended their working relationship.\n|-\n|[[NWA North American Tag Team Championship (Los Angeles/Japan version)|NWA North American Tag Team Championship]]\n|[[Riki Choshu]] and [[Seiji Sakaguchi]]\n|1<br>(1, 5)\n|April 23, 1981\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|It served as NJPW's primary [[tag team]] championship between 1973 and 1981. Abandoned for undocumented reasons.\n|-\n|[[Real World Championship|World Heavyweight Championship]]\n|[[Karl Gotch]]\n|2\n|1972\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|Abandoned for undocumented reasons.\n|}\n\n==Events==\n===Marquee events===\n{{see also|List of New Japan Pro-Wrestling pay-per-view events}}\n*[[Wrestle Kingdom]]\n*[[NJPW The New Beginning|The New Beginning]]\n*[[NJPW Anniversary Show]]\n*[[Wrestling Hinokuni]]\n*[[Wrestling Dontaku]]\n*[[NJPW Dominion|Dominion]]\n*[[Wrestle Dynasty]]\n*[[NJPW Destruction|Destruction]]\n*[[Fighting Spirit Unleashed]]\n*[[King of Pro-Wrestling]]\n*[[NJPW Power Struggle|Power Struggle]]\n\n===Collaborated events===\n*[[Fantastica Mania]] (with CMLL)\n*[[G1 Supercard]] (with ROH)\n*[[Global Wars]] (with ROH)\n*[[Global Wars UK]] (with [[Revolution Pro Wrestling|RPW]])\n*[[Honor Rising: Japan]] (with ROH)\n*[[ROH/NJPW War of the Worlds|War of the Worlds]] (with ROH)\n*[[War of the Worlds UK]] (with ROH, CMLL, RPW)\n\n===Developmental events===\n*[[Lion's Gate Project]]\n*[[Lion's Break Project]]\n\n===Tournaments===\n{{see also|List of New Japan Pro-Wrestling tournaments}}\n\n====Active====\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align:c